  "prompt": "What is the acceptable TDS level of drinking water?",
  "response": "The acceptable Total Dissolved Solids (TDS) level for drinking water varies slightly between different organizations, but generally:\n\n1. World Health Organization (WHO) recommends:\n- Ideal TDS level: 300-500 mg/L\n- Maximum acceptable limit: 1,000 mg/L\n\n2. U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA):\n- Secondary drinking water standard: Less than 500 mg/L\n- Maximum recommended level: 1,000 mg/L\n\n3. General guidelines:\n- 0-50 mg/L: Excellent water quality\n- 50-150 mg/L: Good water quality\n- 150-250 mg/L: Fair water quality\n- 250-300 mg/L: Poor water quality\n- 300-500 mg/L: Acceptable\n- 500-900 mg/L: Poor, not recommended\n- 900-1,200 mg/L: Unacceptable\n- Above 1,200 mg/L: Highly unacceptable\n\nLower TDS levels generally indicate purer water with fewer dissolved minerals and contaminants. However, some minerals are beneficial for health, so extremely low TDS is not always ideal.",
